Below is one way to “highlight” a part of the pixelated GIF. In this example, you already saw a first frame that was a 30×30 grid where the border, main diagonal, and anti‐diagonal were marked by 1’s, 2’s, and 3’s respectively. Now imagine that we want to emphasize (or “highlight”) the very center of that design—in many pixel‐art animations the central region might “glow” or change color to draw attention. Here we’ll define the highlight as the central 2×2 block (that is, the four cells where the diagonals cross) and mark them with a new value (9) to indicate the enhanced glow. (Of course, the “highlight” could be any region you’d like!)

One way to show this is to produce a new 30×30 matrix based on the original rules, with one extra step: if a cell lies at row 14 or 15 and column 14 or 15, then we set its value to 9 (regardless of whether it would normally be a 2 or 3). (Recall that with a 0‐indexed 30×30 grid the “center” lies on rows 14 and 15 and columns 14 and 15.)

Below is a Python code snippet that constructs this “highlight layer,” prints out the matrix (as a list of lists), and even generates an image using matplotlib. (You can run this code in your Python environment.)

───────────────────────────────────── 
# Python Code to Generate Highlighted GIF Frame

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.colors as mcolors

# Create a 30x30 grid
grid = np.zeros((30, 30), dtype=int)

# Fill in the grid based on the original rules:
# • Border pixels (i=0, i=29, j=0, or j=29) get value 1.
# • Main diagonal (j == i) gets value 2.
# • Anti‐diagonal (j == 29 - i) gets value 3.
for i in range(30):
    for j in range(30):
        if i == 0 or i == 29 or j == 0 or j == 29:
            grid[i, j] = 1
        elif j == i:
            grid[i, j] = 2
        elif j == 29 - i:
            grid[i, j] = 3

# Now “highlight” the center 2x2 block:
# For a 30x30 grid the center lies at rows 14 and 15, columns 14 and 15.
highlight_coords = [(14, 14), (14, 15), (15, 14), (15, 15)]
for (i, j) in highlight_coords:
    grid[i, j] = 9

# Print the final matrix as a list-of-lists
print("Highlighted 30x30 Grid (matrix representation):")
print(grid.tolist())

# Optionally, generate an image for the highlighted frame.
# Define a color map (you can adjust these colors as you prefer)
cmap = mcolors.ListedColormap([
    "black",      # 0: background
    "gray",       # 1: border
    "blue",       # 2: main diagonal
    "green",      # 3: anti-diagonal
    "red"         # 9: highlight (red glow)
])
# Normalization: ensure that our values map correctly.
bounds = [0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 10]  # note that our values are 0, 1, 2, 3, and 9.
norm = mcolors.BoundaryNorm(bounds, cmap.N)

plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
plt.imshow(grid, cmap=cmap, norm=norm)
plt.title("Highlight Part of the Pixelated GIF (30x30 grid)")
plt.colorbar(ticks=[0, 1, 2, 3, 9], label="Pixel Value")
plt.show()

───────────────────────────────────── 

Explanation:
1. The grid is built by first setting:
  • The border (first/last row or column) to 1.
  • The main diagonal (i = j) to 2.
  • The anti-diagonal (j = 29 - i) to 3.
2. Then we override the center 2×2 block (cells at (14,14), (14,15), (15,14) and (15,15)) to be 9. This marks them as “highlighted” (imagine a glowing effect in an animated GIF).
3. Finally, we both print the matrix and plot it (using a custom colormap) so that you can visually inspect the highlight.

If you examine the printed matrix, you’ll see that most of it remains as before, with the exception of the four central cells now holding the value 9. The generated image will also show this highlight in a distinct color (red in this case).

Feel free to adjust the region or the highlight value based on your creative needs. Enjoy exploring this pixelated abstraction!

Below is one complete ARC‐style task where the transformation “rotates the center block” of a 10×10 grid. In this task the input is always a 10×10 grid and the “center block” is defined as the 2×2 subgrid in rows (n/2–1, n/2) and columns (n/2–1, n/2) (using 0‐indexed coordinates). The output is the same grid except that the center block has been rotated clockwise 90° (so that, for example, a block originally

  [[A, B],
   [C, D]]

becomes

  [[C, A],
   [D, B]]).

Below you will find three training examples (input–output pairs) and one test pair. Following that is an analogy description and a complete solution program written using Michael Hodel’s DSL.

ARC Task: Rotate Center Block

Description:
 • Given a 10×10 grid, identify the center block defined as the 2×2 subgrid with top‐left corner at (n/2–1, n/2–1) (for n = 10, that is at (4,4)).  
 • Rotate that 2×2 block clockwise 90° and “paste” it back in the same location.  
 • All other cells remain unchanged.

The clockwise rotation of a 2×2 block works as follows:
  [[a, b],
   [c, d]]  →  [[c, a],
   [d, b]]

Analogy:
This task is analogous to “highlighting” a central feature (like a glowing emblem) of a picture and then applying a slight transformation (rotation) to that emphasis. In each ARC example the structure of the grid remains unchanged except for the center. The transformation is solved by combining operations for cropping, rotating, and pasting—much like combining building‐block DSL functions.

────────────────────────────
Solution Program (using Hodel DSL):

Below is one complete program written with the provided DSL functions. It defines a function solve(grid) that:

 1. Computes the “center” position based on the grid’s dimensions.
 2. Extracts the center 2×2 block using crop.
 3. Rotates that block clockwise via rot90.
 4. Replaces the corresponding cells in the original grid with the rotated block.
 5. Returns the new grid.

--------------------------------------------------
from arc_types import *

def solve(grid: Grid) -> Grid:
    # Assume grid is 10x10.
    n = len(grid)
    # For a 10x10 grid, the center block top‐left corner is at (n//2 - 1, n//2 - 1) = (4,4)
    start = (n // 2 - 1, n // 2 - 1)
    dims = (2, 2)
    
    # Extract the center 2x2 block.
    center_block = crop(grid, start, dims)
    
    # Rotate the block clockwise 90° using the DSL function rot90.
    rotated_block = rot90(center_block)
    
    # Convert grid into a mutable list-of-lists.
    new_grid = [list(row) for row in grid]
    
    # Overwrite the center block with the rotated block.
    for i in range(dims[0]):
        for j in range(dims[1]):
            new_grid[start[0] + i][start[1] + j] = rotated_block[i][j]
    
    # Convert back to tuple of tuples.
    return tuple(tuple(row) for row in new_grid)

# For testing purposes, you can run the solve function on any ARC grid input.
--------------------------------------------------

Explanation of DSL Usage:
 • crop(grid, start, dims) extracts the center block.
 • rot90(grid) performs a quarter‐clockwise rotation.
 • Standard Python loops (allowed within the DSL program) are used to “paste” the rotated block back into the grid.
